Below is an example ARC-style task (with grids no larger than 10×10). The core idea: Take a grid, find the most frequent (majority) color, and replace every cell of that color with 9. All remaining colors remain as they are.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1) ARC-Like Task Description
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
• The puzzle has three training input-output pairs and one test pair.  
• For each input grid, identify whichever color occurs most frequently.  
• Transform all cells of that color into the value 9.  
• Produce the resulting grid as the output.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

“The puzzle is to identify the majority color in each grid, then recolor every cell of that majority color to 9.”

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
5) Program Using Hodel’s DSL
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Below is a concise solution in Hodel’s DSL terms:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
from arc_types import *

def solve(grid: Grid) -> Grid:
    # 1. Find the most common color in the grid
    mc = mostcolor(grid)
    # 2. Replace that color with 9
    return replace(grid, mc, 9)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Explanation of the DSL usage:  
• mostcolor(grid) returns the color that appears most frequently in grid.  
• replace(grid, mc, 9) returns a new grid in which all instances of color mc become 9 (all other colors remain the same).  

This completes the ARC-like problem specification and example solution.
